T1  - Rationalization effects of tariff reductions
AU  - Head, Keith
AU  - Ries, John
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
SP  - 295
EP  - 320
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/04/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(98)00019-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199698000191
KW  - Trade policy
KW  - Imperfect competition
KW  - Scale
AB  - We analyze a panel of 230 Canadian manufacturing industries to investigate whether trade liberalization promotes efficiency through increased scale. During the six years following the Free Trade Agreement with the United States, Canadian manufacturing exhibited substantial rationalization – a decline in the number of plants accompanied by increases in output per plant. We find that the bilateral tariff reductions had opposing effects on scale. Contraction induced by lower Canadian tariffs largely offset the 10% scale increase caused by U.S. tariff cuts. The observed increase in scale arose due to currency depreciation, compositional shifts towards high-scale industries, and undercounting of small establishments.
